itish royalty and the Parisian avant-garde. Dances were better boundary crossers than their dancers, however, and the issues of race and class that haunt everyday life shadow American dance as well. Deftly narrated, America Dancing demonstrates the centrality of dance in American art, life, and identity, taking us to watershed moments when the nation worked out a sense of itself through public movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Apr 2020) 0aDancexHistoryxUnited States. 0aDancezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPopular culturexUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300216653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300216653.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO